data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has three .NET Framework APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`** on .NET 8:

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | Kills thread after deadline |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Worker thread | Control flow |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Worker thread | Swallows abort |

All three are part of a single **timeout enforcement** pattern. The replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` + `Task.Run`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. Work doesn't stop automatically.** `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread — cooperative cancellation does not. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop, it keeps running in the background after timeout. To fix this, accept and check a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks.

**3. `Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+.** If you target older runtimes, use `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout))` instead.

**4. Uncooperative third-party code.** If `work()` calls a library you can't modify and it blocks indefinitely, the only true kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` — move it to a child process.

**5. Exception wrapping differs.** The original threw `AggregateException(innerEx)`. `Task.Run` wraps in its own `AggregateException`. The migrated code unwraps to match the original behavior.
